06220nam a22007935i 9781487519926DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192018onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875199267 a10.3138/97814875199262doi  a(DE-B1597)521258  a(OCoLC)1066115392  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aJC571b.R478 2018 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a17222300aResurgence and Reconciliation :bIndigenous-Settler Relations and Earth Teachings /ced. by Michael Asch, James Tully, John Borrows. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One -- t1. Confederation Treaties and Reconciliation: Stepping Back into the Future -- t2. Earth-Bound: Indigenous Resurgence and Environmental Reconciliation -- t3. Reconciliation Here on Earth -- tPart Two -- t4. Rooted Constitutionalism: Growing Political Community -- t5. Towards a Relational Paradigm − Four Points for Consideration: Knowledge, Gender, Land, and Modernity -- t6. Reconciliation and Resurgence: Reflections on the TRC Final Report -- t7. Reconciliation, Resurgence, and Revitalization: Collaborative Research Protocols with Contemporary First Nations Communities -- t8. Proceed with Caution: Reflections on Resurgence and Reconciliation -- t9. Learning from the Earth, Learning from Each Other: Ethnoecology, Responsibility, and Reciprocity -- t10. Indigenous and Crown Sovereignty in Canada -- t11. Treaty Ecologies: With Persons, Peoples, Animals, and the Land -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe two major schools of thought in Indigenous-Settler relations on the ground, in the courts, in public policy, and in research are resurgence and reconciliation. Resurgence refers to practices of Indigenous self-determination and cultural renewal whereas reconciliation refers to practices of reconciliation between Indigenous and Settler nations, such as nation-with-nation treaty negotiations. Reconciliation also refers to the sustainable reconciliation of both Indigenous and Settler peoples with the living earth as the grounds for both resurgence and Indigenous-Settler reconciliation. Critically and constructively analyzing these two schools from a wide variety of perspectives and lived experiences, this volume connects both discourses to the ecosystem dynamics that animate the living earth. Resurgence and Reconciliation is multi-disciplinary, blending law, political science, political economy, women's studies, ecology, history, anthropology, sustainability, and climate change. Its dialogic approach strives to put these fields in conversation and draw out the connections and tensions between them. By using “earth-teachings” to inform social practices, the editors and contributors offer a rich, innovative, and holistic way forward in response to the world’s most profound natural and social challenges. This timely volume shows how the complexities and interconnections of resurgence and reconciliation and the living earth are often overlooked in contemporary discourse and debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspects. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  adialogue.  aearth.  aecological.  agender issues.  aindigenous-settler relations.  ajustice.  areconciliation.  aresurgence.  asocial.  ateachings.1 aAsch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsch, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBorrows, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrows, John, eeditor.4edt4http://